        "timestamp": 1722496167
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Could you explain what you want this for? I don't think we should change the meaning of \"pointed\" here, but perhaps can work out a better name if we know the context.</p>",
        "id": 455570749,
        "sender_full_name": "Kim Morrison",
        "timestamp": 1722496204
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>With Steve Awodey and Mario Carneiro, in <a href=\"https://github.com/sinhp/groupoid_model_in_lean4\">groupoid_model_in_lean4</a> we are formalizing the groupoid model of HoTT in Lean, by interpreting the natural model of HoTT into groupoids. The Natural model comes equipped with a type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Ty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> of small types and a type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Tm</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span></span></span></span> of terms. In the groupoid model they are <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>p</mi><mi>d</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">grpd</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>p</mi><msub><mi>d</mi><mo>âˆ™</mo></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> grpd_\\bullet</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1611em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">âˆ™</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">&ZeroWidthSpace;</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> (i.e. the category of pairs <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>G</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>g</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(G, g)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> is a small groupoid and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span></span></span></span> is an object of it). </p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/kn65e5ZyeiahONlChLxIFBP3/Screenshot-2024-08-01-at-9.34.13AM.png\">Screenshot-2024-08-01-at-9.34.13AM.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/kn65e5ZyeiahONlChLxIFBP3/Screenshot-2024-08-01-at-9.34.13AM.png\" title=\"Screenshot-2024-08-01-at-9.34.13AM.png\"><img data-original-dimensions=\"1826x926\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/3121/kn65e5ZyeiahONlChLxIFBP3/Screenshot-2024-08-01-at-9.34.13AM.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>I need <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>p</mi><msub><mi>d</mi><mo>âˆ™</mo></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">grpd_\\bullet</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1611em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">âˆ™</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">&ZeroWidthSpace;</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. Formalizing the construction <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mo>âˆ™</mo></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_\\bullet</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1611em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">âˆ™</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">&ZeroWidthSpace;</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for a concrete category is a more general case of this construction.</p>",
        "id": 455576133,
        "sender_full_name": "Sina Hazratpour ð“ƒµ",
        "timestamp": 1722497850
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For pointed groupoids, the <code>Under (âŠ¥_ C)</code> approach is the right one though. Do you specifically need \"pointed groups\"?</p>",
        "id": 455576879,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Yang",
        "timestamp": 1722498085
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed. However, I thought maybe in mathlib it would be better  to have a construction that covers groups, rings, fields, topological spaces ..., as well as groupoids and categories? That's why I opted for this formalization. In this project I don't need groups.</p>",
        "id": 455577217,
        "sender_full_name": "Sina Hazratpour ð“ƒµ",
        "timestamp": 1722498207
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I think that general construction is not generally useful, while the <code>Under (âŠ¥_ C)</code> construction is. I'd want to see actual applications!</p>",
        "id": 455593628,
        "sender_full_name": "Kim Morrison",
        "timestamp": 1722502537
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110087\">@Kim Morrison</span> <br>\nI am gravitating to to your position. Other than the pair <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\mathbb{Z} [x], x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> which is the initial object of pointed rings and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>+</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">((\\mathbb{Z},+), 1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">((</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> which is the initial object of pointed groups, I know no other examples.</p>",
        "id": 455594861,
        "sender_full_name": "Sina Hazratpour ð“ƒµ",
        "timestamp": 1722502901
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the \"under bot\" definition is wrong in any category with a zero object. That's how we came up with the group example in the first place</p>",
        "id": 456220672,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1722717857
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The fact that these are simply different constructions tells me that we should probably just have both, and if we do I think the concrete category definition is more deserving of the name \"pointed C\" than the <code>Under (âŠ¥_ C)</code> definition, since it actually involves points and not just global elements.</p>",
        "id": 456220849,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1722718022
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(NB: I discussed this example with Sina beforehand and suggested the concrete category generalization)</p>",
        "id": 456220962,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1722718101
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the established use of \"pointed object\" in the literature is sufficient for that version to claim the name.</p>",
        "id": 456425321,
        "sender_full_name": "Kim Morrison",
        "timestamp": 1722826268
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We could have <code>Pointed</code> for the general <code>Under top</code> construction, and <code>PointedDiscrete</code> for the concrete version. Also, why not making <code>PointedDiscrete</code> an abbreviation for <code>(forget C).Elements</code>?</p>",
        "id": 456427720,
        "sender_full_name": "JoÃ«l Riou",
        "timestamp": 1722827333
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like your suggestions of <code>PointedConcrete</code> and <code>Pointed</code>. </p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"459699\">@JoÃ«l Riou</span> wrote</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Also, why not making PointedDiscrete an abbreviation for (forget C).Elements?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The reason I started with the current definition </p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">class</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Pointed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">where</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">obj</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">C</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">pt</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">obj</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>is because I thought the API might be simpler to use compared to <code>(forget C).Elements</code>. I'll do a parallel formalization using <code>(forget C).Elements</code> and see which one works best.  The advantage of the latter is lemmas/theorems of Elements become immediately available for <code>PointedConcrete</code>, before we prove the equivalence of the two. If the API is not too bad I prefer the second approach too.</p>",
        "id": 456481906,
        "sender_full_name": "Sina Hazratpour ð“ƒµ",
        "timestamp": 1722847737
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The API of <code>Elements</code> may require some improvements, but this is a good occasion to do so!</p>",
        "id": 456483048,
        "sender_full_name": "JoÃ«l Riou",
        "timestamp": 1722848043
    }
